Trim the root and the dark green leafy part from the @leek{1}. Halve lengthways, then
thinly slice widthways.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Roughly chop the
@flat leaf parsley{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all). Halve the @red chilli{1/2}
lengthways, deseed, then thinly slice.

Pour the @water{750%ml} for the stock into a pan and add the @vegetable stock paste{20%g}.
Pop on high heat and bring to the boil. Stir, then reduce the heat to low to keep it
warm.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large pan on medium heat. Once hot, add the leek and
fry until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Stir occasionally.

Once soft, stir in the garlic and @tomato puree{30%g} (and a drizzle more oil if
it's a bit dry). Stir and cook for ~{1%minute}.

Add the @risotto rice{175%g}, then stir and cook for ~{1%minute} until the edges of
the rice are translucent.

Add the @cider vinegar{15%ml} and allow it to evaporate, ~{30%seconds}.

Stir a ladle of stock into the rice pan. When the stock has been absorbed by the rice,
stir in another ladle of stock.

Keep the pan on medium heat and continue stirring in stock, letting it absorb each time.
The cooking time should be ~{20-25%minutes}. Your risotto is done when your rice is
'al dente' - cooked through but with a tiny bit of firmness left in the middle.

> TIP: You may not need all your stock or you may need to add a bit of extra water.

When the risotto has ~{5%minutes} cooking time left, stir in the @king prawns{300%g}
and simmer until they are cooked, ~{5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. The prawns are
> cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Once cooked, remove the risotto from the heat and add the @grated hard Italian style
cheese{40%g}, a knob of @?butter{} (if you have some) and half the parsley.

Stir vigorously until the cheese and butter have melted.

Taste the risotto and add @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} if needed.

Serve your prawn and tomato risotto in bowls with the red chilli (use less chilli if
you don't like heat) and the remaining parsley sprinkled on top. Enjoy!

> Step 4 MOD: If you've chosen to double up on king prawns, cook the recipe in the same
> way.